Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows how you can expose a C++ iterator (the one that libpcapng provides) to Python, while giving Python users a natural‑looking API that lets them:

* iterate over frames with a normal Python `for … in …` loop, **or**
* hand a Python callable to a `for_each` helper that will be invoked for every frame as the C++ iterator walks the collection.

The example uses **pybind11** (the de‑facto standard for C++/Python bindings) and demonstrates the necessary GIL handling, type conversion, and packaging of the binding as a ready‑to‑compile CMake project.

---

## 1. High‑level design (what the Python user sees)

```python
>>> import pcapng
>>> cap = pcapng.Reader("sample.pcapng")          # open a file

# 1️⃣  Classic Python iteration
>>> for frame in cap:                              # Frame objects are yielded
...     print(frame.timestamp, frame.len)

# 2️⃣  Callback style – useful when you want to keep the iteration in C++
>>> def my_handler(frame: pcapng.Frame) -> None:
...     # do something heavy, maybe push to a queue, store stats, etc.
...     print("Got a frame of length", frame.len)

>>> cap.for_each(my_handler)                      # C++ drives the loop,
...                                                # Python callback is called
```

* `pcapng.Reader` – the main entry point, analogous to `libpcapng::Reader`.
* `pcapng.Frame` – a thin wrapper around the underlying C++ `Frame` structure, exposing a few useful read‑only attributes (`timestamp`, `len`, `data`, …).  
  More fields can be added later without breaking the API.
* `Reader.__iter__` – implements the Python iterator protocol.
* `Reader.for_each(callback)` – takes a **Python callable** and calls it for every frame **while the iteration happens on the C++ side** (thus avoiding the Python‑level overhead of the `for … in …` loop). The GIL is released for the bulk of the work and re‑acquired only when the callback is invoked.

---

## 2. Minimal C++ “libpcapng” stub (so the example can be compiled)

> *In a real project you would replace the stub with the genuine libpcapng headers
> (`#include <libpcapng/reader.hpp>` etc.). The stub only mimics the public API we need.*

```cpp
// ------------------------------------------------------------
// file: libpcapng_stub.hpp
// ------------------------------------------------------------
#pragma once
#include <cstdint>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <chrono>
#include <stdexcept>
#include <memory>
#include <fstream>

namespace libpcapng {

using Timestamp = std::chrono::system_clock::time_point;

// ------------------------------------------------------------------
// Frame – a lightweight view of a captured packet
// ------------------------------------------------------------------
class Frame {
public:
    Frame() = default;
    Frame(Timestamp ts, std::vector<uint8_t> payload)
        : ts_(ts), data_(std::move(payload)) {}

    Timestamp timestamp() const noexcept { return ts_; }
    const std::vector<uint8_t>& data() const noexcept { return data_; }
    std::size_t len() const noexcept { return data_.size(); }

private:
    Timestamp ts_{};
    std::vector<uint8_t> data_;
};

// ------------------------------------------------------------------
// Reader – a simple forward‑only iterator over frames in a pcapng file
// ------------------------------------------------------------------
class Reader {
public:
    explicit Reader(const std::string& filename) {
        // *** Very naive “fake” parser *** – just read the whole file as a blob
        // and split it into 1500‑byte chunks, each with a fake timestamp.
        std::ifstream in(filename, std::ios::binary);
        if (!in) throw std::runtime_error("cannot open file: " + filename);
        std::vector<uint8_t> raw((std::istreambuf_iterator<char>(in)),
                                 std::istreambuf_iterator<char>());

        const std::size_t chunk = 1500;
        std::size_t offset = 0;
        auto ts = std::chrono::system_clock::now();
        while (offset < raw.size()) {
            std::size_t sz = std::min(chunk, raw.size() - offset);
            frames_.emplace_back(ts, std::vector<uint8_t>(raw.begin() + offset,
                                                         raw.begin() + offset + sz));
            offset += sz;
            ts += std::chrono::milliseconds(1); // fake spacing
        }
    }

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Forward iterator (C++‑style).  It is deliberately simple: copyable,
    // comparable, dereferencable.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    class iterator {
    public:
        using iterator_category = std::forward_iterator_tag;
        using value_type        = Frame;
        using difference_type   = std::ptrdiff_t;
        using pointer           = const Frame*;
        using reference         = const Frame&;

        iterator() = default;
        explicit iterator(const std::vector<Frame>::const_iterator& it) : it_(it) {}

        reference operator*() const  { return *it_; }
        pointer   operator->() const { return &*it_; }

        iterator& operator++() { ++it_; return *this; }
        iterator  operator++(int) { iterator tmp = *this; ++it_; return tmp; }

        bool operator==(const iterator& other) const noexcept { return it_ == other.it_; }
        bool operator!=(const iterator& other) const noexcept { return it_ != other.it_; }

    private:
        std::vector<Frame>::const_iterator it_;
    };

    iterator begin() const noexcept { return iterator(frames_.cbegin()); }
    iterator end()   const noexcept { return iterator(frames_.cend()); }

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Helper that drives the iteration on the C++ side and calls a user‑supplied
    // functor for each frame.  The functor is a template so we can pass a
    // pybind11::object (which is a callable) without any extra wrappers.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    template <typename Callable>
    void for_each(Callable&& cb) const {
        for (const auto& f : frames_) {
            // The caller (pybind11) will have released the GIL before we get here.
            // We *re‑acquire* it only while calling the user callback.
            pybind11::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;
            cb(f);
        }
    }

private:
    std::vector<Frame> frames_;
};

} // namespace libpcapng
```

> **Note** – The stub implements everything needed for the binding:
> * a `Frame` class with a timestamp and a data buffer,
> * a forward iterator (`Reader::iterator`),
> * a `Reader::for_each` template method that can accept any callable.

